eover of Congress. The 2026 midterms have to be the next target for despond=
ent Democrats, even if voters out there in the country aren=E2=80=99t very =
excited about what the party is selling.

Rahm, who helped engineer the party=E2=80=99s comeback in 2006 as head of t=
he Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, recruited candidates who di=
dn=E2=80=99t
fit neatly into the usual Jell-O mold. =E2=80=8B=E2=80=9CI remember distinc=
tly being told when I was reaching out to candidates that these aren=E2=80=
=99t real Democrats,=E2=80=9D he told me Monday. =E2=80=9CBut that was the =
whole premise! If you are going to flip a district, you have to recruit peo=
ple who are going to make a cultural connection in that district. The goal =
wasn=E2=80=99t to make you feel comfortable in Washington or the Upper West=
 Side or Beverly Hills. It=E2=80=99s about winning, you dummies.=E2=80=9D

Punching Left

Democrats, Rahm continued, need to put aside purity tests and find candidat=
es who aren=E2=80=99t afraid to piss off the language police and progressiv=
e scolds that seem to spook so many operatives in the party. Emanuel sounde=
d exasperated when he recalled how progressives savaged Biden after he used=
 the term =E2=80=9Cillegal alien=E2=80=9D in his State of the Union address=
 earlier this year, a comment he was forced to apologize for. =E2=80=9CYou =
are illegally coming across the border, and you are an immigrant,=E2=80=9D =
said Emanuel. =E2=80=9CI mean, come on.=E2=80=9D

Emanuel said that Democrats need to remind voters that they are the party o=
f the little guy, standing up to big banks and billionaires. He also put a =
blunter edge on a sentiment I=E2=80=99d heard a lot from pragmatic strategi=
sts in recent years: That Democrats can only win when they start punching l=
eft and pushing
back against the orthodoxies that have spread from elite campuses into part=
y committees and big-city newsrooms. Grad school concepts about identity, g=
ender, race, or crime that are either unpopular, inscrutable, or far remove=
d from people=E2=80=99s daily lives.

That=E2=80=99s one reason certain Senate candidates, including members of t=
he =E2=80=9906 class such as Jon Tester and Sherrod Brown, outran Harris in=
 red states, he said. And it explains why winning candidates Tammy Baldwin,=
 Ruben Gallego, and Jacky Rosen have white-knuckled their way to victory. T=
hey didn=E2=80=99t let their races get nationalized, and they worked overti=
me to talk less about Trump and the culture wars, and more about the kitche=
n table. =E2=80=9CWe don=E2=80=99t understand that working-class people are=
 more than just the summation of their wallet,=E2=80=9D Emanuel said. =E2=
=80=9CThey have kids that go to school. They care about public safety. Like=
, we are telling people
crime is going down, but they go to CVS and everything is locked up and no =
one is working there? That doesn=E2=80=99t compute, I=E2=80=99m sorry. Save=
 your academic presentations for the Aspen Ideas Festival.=E2=80=9D

Punching left, of course, is more easily said than done, as Congressman Set=
h Moulton learned over the weekend when he spoke to The New York Times with=
 unusual honesty about trans athletes playing in women=E2=80=99s and girls =
sports. =E2=80=9CI have two little girls, I don=E2=80=99t want them getting=
 run over on a playing field by a male or formerly male athlete, but as a D=
emocrat I=E2=80=99m supposed to be afraid to say that.=E2=80=9D One of Moul=
ton=E2=80=99s staffers resigned in protest, and he was condemned by the hea=
d of the Massachusetts Democratic Party. At the same time, in polls, large =
majorities of the country agree with Moulton=E2=80=99s take.

There=E2=80=99s no simple blueprint here. The only consensus I=E2=80=99ve b=
een able to pick up on from Democrats, however vague, is that the
party needs to get back to listening to voters rather than talking at them.=
 Congresswoman Marie Gluesenkamp Perez, a flannel-wearing Democrat who won =
reelection last week in a southwestern Washington district that also voted =
for Trump, has been doing the media rounds the last few days explaining how=
 she pulled out her race while other Democrats stumbled in what was a terri=
ble political environment. But when I talked to her Monday, even she acknow=
ledged there were limits to how much national Democrats could learn from he=
r win. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t want to be a poster child or a cardboard cu=
tout,=E2=80=9D Gluesenkamp Perez told me. =E2=80=9CIf there is a model here=
, it=E2=80=99s just that you have to fight for where you come from, to show=
 up and do the work. That has to be the motivator, and it=E2=80=99s how you=
 break the ideological map.=E2=80=9D

