x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Congress returns to=
 the Capitol this week, and it=E2=80=99s back to the <b>Trump </b>reality s=
how and the familiar question: How much pressure will the once and future p=
resident exert on Capitol Hill? While much of the media is consumed by post=
-election navel-gazing and 2028 catastrophizing, Trump=E2=80=99s MAGA allie=
s are barreling ahead and already showing a propensity to piss off the Sena=
te in ways they didn=E2=80=99t dare during Trump=E2=80=99s first rodeo. The=
 president-elect, meanwhile, is running roughshod over the Republicans=E2=
=80=99 narrow margin in the House as he looks to staff up his administratio=
n. Here are some emerging themes=E2=80=A6<br/><br/><ul style=3D"margin:0;co=
lor:#000000;font-size:16px;line-height:30px;margin-top:0;margin-bottom:0;li=
st-style-type:square;mso-special-format:bullet"><li><i>Bannon bullies the S=
enate</i>: MAGA warriors spent the last day or so
arm-twisting Republican senators in a bid to garner support for Florida=E2=
=80=99s<b> Rick Scott </b>as Senate majority leader, a move that would bypa=
ss <i>The Johns</i>, <b>Thune </b>and<b> Cornyn</b>, who have worked meticu=
lously for years to cultivate relationships with colleagues in preparation =
for this moment. Acknowledging the secret ballot selection process, <b>Stev=
e Bannon</b> and others are demanding a public vote, which is anathema to b=
asically every leadership race on the Hill, outside of a speaker=E2=80=99s =
floor vote. <br/><br/>Most G.O.P. senators, of course, <i>hate</i> this ide=
a. Will they stand up to Bannon=E2=80=99s pressure and set a small but subs=
tantive precedent of pushback from the Hill against Trump allies? It=E2=80=
=99s a safe bet, regardless, that MAGA voters will be calling these offices=
, demanding the senators reveal who they support, which could translate int=
o angry constituents. (Thoughts and prayers for Senate Republican staff ass=
istants manning the phones today.) On
the other hand, if MAGA prevails in this push for a loyalty oath, prepare f=
or a whole new ball game on Capitol Hill. </li><br/><li><i>Manic Monday in =
the House</i>: The speed with which Trump plucked <b>Elise Stefanik</b> to =
be U.S. ambassador to the United Nations caught <i>some</i> members off gua=
rd, even though it was common knowledge she was angling for an administrati=
on post. What was even more startling on Monday evening was <b>Kaitlan Coll=
ins</b>=E2=80=99 report that Trump was <i>also </i>plucking Florida Rep. <b=
>Mike Waltz</b> from the House to serve as National Security Advisor. Becau=
se that post doesn=E2=80=99t require Senate confirmation, this will be an e=
arly vacancy. As late as Friday, it seemed impossible to House insiders tha=
t Trump would mine their talent pool, due to the tight margin coming out of=
 this election. More of the outstanding races have fallen Republicans=E2=80=
=99 way, but every one of these appointments creates a more stressful G.O.P=
=2E headcount. Waltz, at least,
represents a safe Republican seat, and will likely be replaced by a fellow =
conservative. <br/><br/>Stefanik=E2=80=99s exit, however, will have greater=
 repercussions, setting off a race for her conference chair leadership post=
, with Michigan=E2=80=99s <b>Lisa McClain</b>, Florida=E2=80=99s <b>Kat Cam=
mack</b>, and Indiana=E2=80=99s <b>Erin Houchin </b>all vying for the nod. =
Assuming she passes confirmation, Stefanik=E2=80=99s assignment to the East=
 River will create a vacancy early next year in her upstate New York distri=
ct: Once a competitive seat, New York=E2=80=99s 21st has become safe Republ=
ican territory because of the rural conservative drift, the latest redistri=
cting, and the strength of Stefanik=E2=80=99s incumbency. <br/><br/>Democra=
ts are giving this potential race a look, but they don=E2=80=99t seem terri=
bly inclined to make a major investment there on par with <b>Tom Suozzi</b>=
=E2=80=99s New York 3rd District special election earlier this year. Now, s=
ome might argue this could be a test case for the midterms. During
Trump=E2=80=99s first term, he chose seven-term Congressman <b>Tom Price </=
b>of Georgia as his health and human services secretary=E2=80=94only to see=
 Price=E2=80=99s once-safe suburban Republican seat, formerly occupied by <=
b>Newt</b> <b>Gingrich</b>, become competitive in a special election, which=
 in turn led to the most expensive House race in history. The Democratic ca=
ndidate in that special, <b>Jon Ossoff</b>, only lost by 3 points, a harbin=
ger of the coming blue wave in 2018.  <br/><br/>Just prior to his White Hou=
se appointment, Price had won reelection by a 23-point margin; Stefanik won=
 her bid for reelection last week by 25 points. But the rural nature of thi=
s district probably makes the Stefanik seat a heavier lift than the Price s=
eat. In any case, the potential Stefanik vacancy from Congress will be an a=
nnoyance for Johnson and the leadership team as they count votes next year.=
 A New York special election to fill Stefanik=E2=80=99s seat could test Dem=
ocratic enthusiasm (or lack thereof)
after such a depressing cycle. And the political climate could shift dramat=
ically over the next six months, as voters become reacquainted with the Tru=
mp chaos. <br/></li></ul></td>
         </tr>
